                                                                                                               Safe food demand in state
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, May 23: Living Farms, a city-based organisation and a member of the United Coalition Against Genetic Engineering, has urged the state government to take all steps to ensure a genetically modified-free Orissa.         
	It has also requested chief minister Naveen Patnaik to keep the public informed about his governments decision. The progress of the state depends on how healthy and mature its citizens are, it said in a letter to Naveen.        
	Pointing out that doctors of the American Academy of Environmental Medicine had asked for an immediate moratorium on genetically modified food  requesting all physicians to instruct people not to consume the same  the letter said that a few scientists we re leaving no stone unturned to introduce this dangerous food into the food chain.        
	People of Orissa do not need new diseases or hospitals. What we need is adequate, safe, natural, non-toxic and nutritious food, livelihood security, a clean environment, favourable weather conditions and freedom from pollution, poisonous gases and toxins, activists said.        
	Considering the disastrous performance of BT Cotton and its adverse impact on soil, animals and people in Orissa, we hope that your government will ensure a safer Orissa.                                                                                                                                                                           
